<item>
            <title>[JDK-8304301] Remove the global option SuperWordMaxVectorSize</title>
                <link>https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8304301</link>
                <project id="10100" key="JDK">JDK</project>
                    <description>See the discussion in &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8877#issuecomment-1144247578&quot;&gt;https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8877#issuecomment-1144247578&lt;/a&gt;. The option SuperWordMaxVectorSize was introduced in JDK19 as a temporary solution to fix a performance issue on x86 cascade lake machines. The implementation is fine for current aarch64 hardware, but SVE architectures supports more than 512 bits. &lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Also, the patch handled SuperWordMaxVectorSize on vm version level only for x86 platform and missed other platforms, see the discussion in &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/12350#discussion_r1126106213&quot;&gt;https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/12350#discussion_r1126106213&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
The task is to drop the global option but keep the performance fix on the x86 backend, to reduce side effect for other platforms.</description>
